  "observation": "Brainstorm triggered by plateau. 4 proposals generated.",
  "suggestion": "Evolution is stuck because the fitness landscape is static and the mutation space has been exhaustively explored under current architectural constraints. Organisms have found the local optimum for a fixed world with fixed interaction rules. The plateau is not a sign of convergence to truth — it's a sign of architectural suffocation. Adding coevolution (dynamic landscape), novelty reward (multi-modal fitness), and generative morphology (explosive mutation space) together break the constraint ceiling. The system optimizes *design generation* not just *design refinement*.; [medium] Introduce coevolutionary predator-prey dynamics with emergent niche specialization — Current system likely converges to a single organism body plan optimized for current world. Adding organisms with opposing fitness pressures (predators that hunt fast organisms, prey that evolve evasion) creates an arms race that prevents convergence and forces continuous morphological innovation. Predator and prey beauty become interdependent — predator elegance is hunting efficiency, prey elegance is escape artistry. This breaks the plateau by making the fitness landscape non-stationary and multi-modal.; [medium] Replace static beauty metric with emergent ecosystem-level beauty: phylogenetic diversity score that rewards new body plan innovations genetically distinct from recent ancestors — If current beauty metric is phenotypic (shape, color), evolution converges to local optimum. Shift metric to reward structural novelty: organisms with unique body plans relative to lineage history score higher in beauty. This directly incentivizes morphological exploration over exploitation. Organisms stop winning by refining the same design and start winning by inventing new designs. Ties directly to 'being beauty' goal — true beauty is innovation.; [hard] Introduce substrate-level growth physics: organisms no longer have fixed cell types, but can spawn specialized cell types mid-development in response to local chemical gradients — Plateau suggests organisms have hit the ceiling of current morphospace under fixed cell types (e.g., photosynthesis cells, muscle cells, sensory cells). Allow adaptive morphogenesis: cells detect neighbor density, nutrient flow, predator pressure and spawn new cell types on-the-fly. This explodes the discovery space — organisms can develop organs they've never evolved before. Requires runtime cell-type invention, not just parameter tuning. Enables reaching entirely new fitness peaks.",
